GOALS

Goal #1 Increase the number of affordable housing units in the City of Santa Barbara by 20%
Goal #2 Strengthen the capacity of organizations that provide permanent housing placement services to increase the rate of housing retention by 5%
Goal #3 Create a culture of diversion and prevention among collaborative partners to reduce the percentage of individuals, youth and families entering homelessness from a housed situation by 10%
Goal #4 Strengthen the coordination and availability of outreach and case management services for individuals, youth and families experiencing homelessness by 25%

COLLABORATIVE STRUCTURE

Steering committee

Data
The Steering Committee exists to provide guidance, vision, and oversight for the ACT on Homelessness Collaborative and the 3-Year Common Agenda (Strategic Plan)

Partners

Partners

SB City Council, SB City Department of Community Development, SB County Housing & Community Development Division, Housing Authority of the City of SB, SB County Department of Behavioral Wellness, SB Public Library, SB Police Department Home for Good SB County, Cottage Center for Population Health, PATH SB, Transition House, New Beginnings Counseling Center, City Net

Row

Meetings

The Steering Committee meets on a quarterly basis to evaluate Collaborative progress toward the 3-year Common Agenda goals, address emerging community-wide needs, and adjust the Common Agenda as needed.

Row

Working groups summary

Working Groups exist to facilitate movement toward the 3-year goals of the Collaborative Common Agenda through the development of strategies and metric indicators. Working Groups are also responsible for the implementation of the strategies of each respective goal.

State Street About The State Street RAP was formed in Fall 2019 with the purpose of reducing the impacts of homelessness in the highest-density 4-block region. Since then, the RAP has expanded to address concerns about the impacts of homelessness throughout the lower State Street region.
State Street Accomplishments Reduced homelessness in 4-block section by 80%, assisted in addressing the impacts of homelessness in front of Marshalls, successfully advocated for 6 public restrooms in strategic locations on State Street

NA Formalization of Neighborhood Navigation Centers In 2021, SB ACT began a formal partnership with the City of Santa Barbara and the Natalie Orfalea Foundation to create Neighborhood Navigation Centers, public sites where individuals experiencing homelessness can find an outdoor one-stop-shop for immediate needs, supportive services, case management, and relational trust-building. As of January 2022, there are currently two NNC sites: The Carrillo Castillo Commuter Lot (Tuesdays 10am-1pm) and Alameda Park (Thursdays 5:30pm-7pm). SB ACT is currently exploring options to establish a third site.
NA Prioritization of Diversion or Rapid Resolution Resources In 2021, SB ACT worked with the City to establish a $20,000 Whatever It Takes diversion fund for the NNC sites. These funds are to be used for various expenses that go with diverting individuals from homelessness.
